node.text: Welcome to the new era of Martian exploration! Yesterday the world looked on in awe as NASA shared the first video of a rover landing on another planet and the first recording of audio from Mars. Listen to our CEO @billnye as he reacts to this unprecedented moment in history.

node.text: It isn’t easy to defend our planet from asteroids. That’s why we support those who step up to the job.

Star Trek: Voyager's holographic doctor, Robert Picardo, also serves on The Planetary Society Board of Directors. However, he is not the first connection between Star Trek and The Planetary Society. In 1980, the creator of Star Trek, Gene Roddenberry, wrote a letter and sent it out to a Star Trek fans mailing list. In the letter, Gene invited his fans to join us on our mission to explore the cosmos.

Hear the letter as read by Robert Picardo, listen to his Jean-Luc Picard impression, and see inside Bill Nye's office for more Star Trek artifacts on hand at The Planetary Society.

Read the full letter at planetary.org

node.title: A rare letter from Star Trek creator Gene Roddenberry

Who are your favorite space science communicators that you wish everyone knew?

This gorgeous image shows a cloud known as Lupus 3, which lies about 600 light-years from Earth in the constellation of Scorpius (The Scorpion). The section shown here is about five light-years across.

(📸: ESO/F. Comeron)

Ganymede: I know I'm the biggest moon in the solar system, but it's kind of hard to appreciate my achievements when Jupiter is just —

Jupiter: DID YOU SAY MY NAME?

😆

@NASA's Cassini spacecraft caught this image of Jupiter and Ganymede, the largest planet and largest moon in our solar system, on December 3, 2000.

(📸 : NASA/JPL/University of Arizona)

#Jupiter #moon #space

Last week, NASA's Juno spacecraft made its 35th close flyby of Jupiter! Juno snapped a bunch of striking pictures, three of which were combined to make this composite image of our beautiful neighboring gas giant.

If this image of Jupiter was a painting, what would you name it?

(📸 : NASA/JPL-Caltech/SwRI/MSSS/Kevin M. Gill 9@apoapsys))

node.text:
50 years ago today the Apollo 15 mission launched, sending three astronauts on the most ambitious mission to the Moon yet. They stayed longer, roved farther, and did more science than any Apollo mission up to that point.

Pictured: 

1. Lightning striking behind the Saturn V rocket the day before it launched the mission. 

2. The lunar module "Falcon" at the foot of the Appenine mountain range. 

3. Astronaut Jim Irwin with Apollo 15's Lunar Roving Vehicle.

4. Apollo 15 astronaut Dave Scott visiting the Genesis Rock, one of the samples his mission returned to Earth, in the Lunar Receiving Laboratory. This was one of the oldest rocks ever studied by scientists, who dated it at over 4 billion years old.

Today marks two years since LightSail 2 unfurled its sails!

Our crowdfunded spacecraft is still sailing on sunlight today, all thanks to people around the world who came together to turn a dream into reality.

node.text:
It's the 45th anniversary of Viking 1's landing on Mars! Viking 1 captured the first close-up image of the surface of the Red Planet shortly after it touched down.

@NASA's Viking 1 landed on Mars on July 20, 1976. It was the second spacecraft in history to touch down on the Red Planet. Viking 1 and 2 were a pair of Mars landers and orbiters that launched in 1975 and arrived in 1976.

Our co-founder Carl Sagan helped design and manage the Viking missions. 🙌

(1: First image of the surface of Mars (NASA), 2: Carl Sagan with Viking lander model (NASA/JPL))

#space #mars #sagan

This morning @BlueOrigin launched its first crew aboard New Shepard.

The passengers on today’s flight were Mercury 13 pilot Wally Funk, physics student Oliver Daemen of the Netherlands, Jeff Bezos, and his brother Mark Bezos. At 18, Daemen is the youngest person to fly to space, and Funk, 82, is the oldest person to become an astronaut.

(📸 : Blue Origin)

node.text:
Today is the 8th anniversary of this iconic image, called "The Day the Earth Smiled."

@NASA's Cassini spacecraft passed into the shadow of Saturn on July 19, 2013, and captured this dramatic shot. "The Day the Earth Smiled" is a mosaic created from 141 Cassini images. In it, we can see the night side of Saturn, seven of its moons, its inner rings, and — if you look carefully — our home planet. Earth is just below the rings on the right side of the image.

If we zoom in close, we can spot our planet and its Moon. They look so small and beautiful.

How does it make you feel to view the Earth from this distance?

(📸 : NASA/JPL-Caltech/SSI)

#Saturn #Earth #space

The Zhurong rover visited its parachute and backshell on Mars.

The China National Space Administration's Zhurong rover landed in Utopia Planitia on the Red Planet on May 14. Zhurong traveled about 350 meters away from its landing site to capture this image on July 12.

(📸 : CNSA/PEC via Andrew Jones)

#mars #science #space

Saturn and Mimas posing for a dramatic photoshoot. Mimas looks a little camera shy.

Saturn's gossamer-thin rings paint with light and shadow across the canvas of Saturn's upper atmosphere in this stunning true-color image captured by NASA's Casini spacecraft on November 7, 2004. The icy moon right of center is Mimas. 

(📸 : NASA / JPL-Caltech / SSI)

#space #Saturn #NASA

node.text:
Enceladus is super extra, in the best way. This moon of Saturn has a subsurface ocean, hydrothermal vents, and sprays so much material into space through cracks in its ice that it forms Saturn's E ring.

These images of Enceladus, its geysers, and Saturn's E ring were taken by @NASA's Cassini spacecraft.

Do you think there might be life in the oceans of Enceladus?

2: Enceladus geysers (NASA/JPL/Space Science Institute)

This beautiful animation of the Ganymede flyby was created from the JunoCam images taken on June 7, 2021. With the power of digital editing, the images were orthographically projected onto a sphere and extra frames were added to make the video run smoothly.
